In article &lt;295@brolga.cc.uq.oz&gt;, ggm@brolga.cc.uq.oz (George Michaelson) asks
if it *really* makes sense to promote such "useful" triglyphs as
.edu .gov .org .com to "top level" status.

You should just pretend that the above top-level domains are under
.US (but in fact are not).  Much like the weather on the 6pm news stops at the
border, so did our international perspective when it came to the initial
structure of the DNS top-level.  I offer an international apology.

I belive that when ISO comes along, the most significant component of relative
distinguished name entry will be the country code.

Geoff Goodfellow
Fernwood.MPK.CA.US (the first host registered in the .US Domain).

